The moniker "booth babe" is also controversial itself as it is considered offensive and degrading by some,<ref name=mash>{{cite news | last = Fox | first =Zoe |url=http://mashable.com/2013/01/11/booth-babes-ces/ |title=CEA on 'Booth Babes': The Name Is the Problem |work=Mashable |date=12 January 2013 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=jal/> including trade show models themselves.<ref name=abc/><ref>{{cite web|last=Peterson |first=Andrea |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2014/02/27/heres-what-its-like-to-be-a-booth-babe-at-cybersecuritys-biggest-conference/ |title=Here’s what it’s like to be a ‘booth babe’ at cybersecurity’s biggest conference |work =The Washington Post |date=25 July 2013 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fremling |first=Alicia |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2014/01/10/ces_2014_what_it_s_like_to_be_a_booth_babe_at_trade_shows.html |title=CES 2014: What it's like to be a "booth babe" at trade shows |work=Slate |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> The term nevertheless continues to be often used by journalists and by the people opposed to the presence of the models they define as "booth babes".

[[File:Girls of E3 2011 - Part 2 No.07.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A model at [[E3 2011]]]]

Changing social and business standards have resulted in a decrease in the use of promotional models in trade shows,<ref name=Sorensen>{{cite news | last = Sorensen | first = Jean |title="Booth babes" fading from tradeshow floors |url=http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id42964 |work=Journal of Commerce |publisher=Reed Elsevier inc |date=February 21, 2011 |accessdate=19 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713121207/http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id42964 |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> especially in the United States.<ref name=cbc/> The largest video gaming business convention, [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3)]], attempted to ban "conduct that is sexually explicit and/or sexually provocative" [[E3 2006|in 2006]] following [[Agetec]]'s 2005 "Anti Booth Babe" protest,<ref>''Citations:'':
* {{cite news|last=Lees |first=Jennie |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2006/01/23/censorship-at-e3/ |title=Censorship at E3 (blog) | work = Joystiq |publisher= Weblogs, Inc. |date=23 January 2006 |accessdate=26 August 2013}}
* {{cite news | last = Glaister | first = Dan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/may/16/worlddispatch.usa |title=Decline of the booth babe |work=The Guardian &#124; World news |date= 16 May 2006 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}
* {{cite news| last = Cangeloso | first = Sal |url=http://www.geek.com/xyzcomputing/company-takes-stand-against-booth-babes-571259/ |title=Company takes stand against booth babes |work=Geek.com &#124; xyzcomputing |date=13 May 2005 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}
* {{cite news| last = Terdiman | first = Daniel|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/despite-controversy-booth-babes-still-prowl-e3/ |title=Despite controversy, 'booth babes' still prowl E3 |work=CNET News  | date = 23 March 2009 |accessdate= 21 July 2014}}</ref> but reversed on this stance [[E3 2009|in 2009]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Purchese |first=Robert |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/e3-booth-babes-to-return-this-year |title=E3 Booth babes to return this year |work=Eurogamer|date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> after complaints regarding this and other policy changes.<ref name=bbc/> [[GameSpot]]'s [[Greg Kasavin]] commented that, with this attempt, the [[Entertainment Software Association|Entertainment Software Association (ESA)]] was "trying to put a definition to what constitutes scantily clad and what's borderline offensive" as it was "under a lot of pressure these days to clean up the image of games and to at least demonstrate that the video-game industry is responsible in regulating itself" in the aftermath of [[Hot Coffee mod]] controversy.<ref name=abc/>

[[China Digital Entertainment Expo & Conference]] (China Joy) introduced and strictly enforced a [[dress code]] in 2012,<ref>{{cite news|last=Matyszczyk |first=Chris |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/gaming-expo-in-china-bans-booth-babes/ |title=Gaming expo in China bans booth babes |work=CNET |date= 2 August 2012 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> saying they did not want "to send the wrong message" to their adolescent primary audience,<ref>{{cite news | last = Carter |first =Johnathan Grey |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/118848-Chinese-Gaming-Expo-Bans-Booth-Babes |title=Chinese gaming expo bans booth babes &#124; The Escapist |publisher=Escapist Magazine |date= |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] banned the [[SuicideGirls]] erotic models from having a booth in 2010.<ref name=rama>{{cite news| last = Rogers | first = Vaneta |url=http://www.newsarama.com/5701-comic-con-wrestles-with-booth-babe-controversy.html |title=Comic-Con wrestles with 'booth babe' controversy |work=Newsarama |date=22 July 2010 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Video game convention [[Penny Arcade Expo|Penny Arcade Expo (PAX)]] adopted a dress codes for both male and female models<ref>{{cite news| last = junglist|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2013/07/so-why-were-there-booth-babes-at-pax-aus |title=So why were there booth babes at PAX Aus? |work=Kotaku | location = Australia | date = 24 July 2013 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> in what they call a "no booth babes" policy guideline, where "booth babes are defined as staff of ANY gender used by exhibitors to promote their products at PAX by using overtly sexual or suggestive methods. Partial nudity, the aggressive display of cleavage and the navel, and shorts/skirts higher than 4” above the knee are not allowed."<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer|url=http://prime.paxsite.com/safety-and-security#booth-babe-policies |title=PAX Prime - Seattle, WA Aug 29-Sep 1, 2014 |publisher=Prime.paxsite.com |date= |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> [[Eurogamer Expo]] did not allow them completely in 2012, saying they wanted to make a more "friendly" show and all visitors "to feel comfortable," with a formal guideline saying "Booth babes are Not OK."<ref>{{cite web | last = Rupert|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/forum/thread/242422 |title=Booth babes and the expo (forum message) |publisher=Eurogamer.net |date=3 October 2012 |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>

The [[Consumer Electronics Association|Consumer Electronics Association (CEA)]], including its president and CEO [[Gary Shapiro]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Danzico | first = Matt |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-16533289 |title='Booth babes' stir controversy at 2012 CES |work=BBC News |date=12 January 2012 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> and senior vice-president Karen Chupka,<ref name=mash/> initially defended the use of female models who were deemed not dressed enough by critics but discouraged the practice in 2014 after a [[Change.org]] petition started by a ''[[Forbes]]'' technology journalist Connie Guglielmo demanded a ban on them and reached 250 signatures.<ref name=bbc/> The campaigners' proposal to "ban booth babes" was rejected as the CEA refused to "create and impose arbitrary or unenforceable rules, or worse, inch our event towards a [[Taliban]]esque ban on exposure of skin,"<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|last=Kelion |first=Leo |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-21373094 |title=CES 'booth babe' guidelines revised but ban rejected |work=BBC News |date= 10 February 2013 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> but the new [[Consumer Electronics Show|Consumer Electronics Show (CES)]] exhibitor guidelines stated, "recent news articles show that ‘booth babes’ can reflect poorly on your exhibit, so we ask that you give this thoughtful consideration, to avoid alienating or offending various audience segments."<ref>{{cite news|last=Duhaime |first=Arielle |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/10/5294440/why-cant-ces-quit-booth-babes |title=Why can't CES quit booth babes? |work=The Verge |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> {{-}}

[[File:Michael Smith - 2017253200332 2017-09-10 PDC German Darts Grand Prix (GDGP) - Sven - 1D X MK II - 0527 - AK8I5181.jpg|thumb|A walk-on girl guiding darter [[Michael Smith (darts player)|Michael Smith]] to the stage in 2017.]]
After a round of talks with broadcasters, the [[Professional Darts Corporation]] announced on 27 January 2018 that it would discontinue the use of '''walk-on girls''' in darts tournaments. The decision has encountered a backlash from some fans, players and models.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/darts/42841620 |title=Darts: PDC to scrap walk-on girls after broadcaster talks |work=BBC Sport |date=27 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> 

On 31 January 2018, [[Formula 1]] management announced that it would end the practice of '''grid girls''' (also known as '''paddock girls''' or '''umbrella girls'''), who accompany the racers to the track, a tradition that "has been a staple of Formula 1 Grands Prix for decades", stating that "[they] feel this custom does not resonate with [their] brand values and clearly is at odds with modern day societal norms."<ref>{{Cite news | last = de Menezes | first = Jack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/formula1/formula-1-f1-grid-girls-banned-get-rid-women-grand-prix-darts-ban-pdc-walk-on-eddie-hearn-a8187161.html |title=Formula 1 to get rid of grid girls before grand prixs in response to darts ban |work=The Independent |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> The move has drawn criticism from former grid girls, including British model [[Kelly Brook]]. Former F1 executive [[Bernie Ecclestone]] and [[Red Bull Racing]] leader [[Christian Horner]] also expressed disapproval.<ref>''Citations:'':
* {{cite news|last1=Wheatstone|first1=Richard|title=Who are the Formula 1 grid girls, how much do they get paid and why are they being banned?|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/5474205/formula-1-grid-girls-ban-salary-kelly-brook/|work=The Sun|subscription = yes|accessdate=4 February 2018|date=3 February 2018}}
* {{cite news|last1=McKern|first1=James|title=‘Tarty nonsense’: F1’s shock grid girl plan|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/motorsport/formula-one/f1-bosses-looking-into-whether-grid-girls-should-continue/news-story/d4c264522fa3316dfa688448465b4c8b|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=4 February 2018|date=15 December 2017}}
* {{cite news|last1=Bhutia|first1=Jigmey|title=Kelly Brook backs F1 grid girls with her throwback photos|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/kelly-brook-sparks-meltdown-breathtaking-photos-her-grid-girl-days-1658505|work=International Business Times UK|accessdate=4 February 2018|language=en|date=3 February 2018}}
* {{cite news | last = Benson | first = Andrew|title=Formula 1: 'Grid girls' will not be used at races this season|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/42890261|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 February 2018|date=31 January 2018}}</ref> 
In February 2018 Formula 1 announced it intended to replace 'grid girls' with a new programme called 'grid kids'<ref>NAANII GLOBAL Motorsport & quality family Lifestyle -Magazin 'en Vogue'-,(21 march 2018), www.naaniiglobal.com, [http://www.naanii.es/blog/index.php?id=828u354h 'First ever australian 'F1 Grid Kids', passioned Karting driver, met with [[Daniel Ricciardo]] prior Australian F1 GP 2018'] </ref> this season. The children used will be competitors in [[karting]] or junior categories, chosen by national motorsport authorities.<ref>{{cite news | last = Benson | first = Andrew | title = Formula 1: 'Grid kids' to replace 'grid girls' from start of the season | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/42950040?ocid=socialflow_facebook&ns_mchannel=social&ns_campaign=bbcnews&ns_source=facebook | work = BBC Sport | date = 5 February 2018 | access-date = 23 February 2018}}</ref> However, they were seen in Monaco Grand Prix this season.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

